eriod from 1870 to 1940, chronicling one generation’s suspicions toward public education and another’s need to assimilate.Through careful research Lassonde finds that not all working class parents were enthusiastic supporters of education. Not only did the time and energy spent in school restrict children’s potential financial contributions to the family, but attitudes that children encountered in school often ran counter to the family’s traditional values. Legally mandated education and child labor laws eventually resolved these conflicts, but not without considerable reluctance and resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aImmigrantsxEducationzConnecticutzNew HavenxHistory. 0aWorking classxEducationzConnecticutzNew HavenxHistory. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030007396640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030012890140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300128901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300128901/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY